yle=\"text-align:right;\"  | 197\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 34\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 40\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 123\n|-\n| [[Taguig]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 199\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 15\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 24\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 160\n|-\n| [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 80\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 6\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 7\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 67\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 4,136\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 451\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 565\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 3120\n|-\n|}\n* January 30 \u2013 The Philippines confirms its first case of coronavirus in Metro Manila and the entire country after a 38-year-old woman from [[Wuhan]] tested positive for COVID-19. She was hospitalized at [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] in Manila.<ref name=\"abs1\"/>\n* February 2 \u2013 The first coronavirus-related death outside China was recorded in Manila. A 44-year-old Chinese man died while being treated at the San Lazaro Hospital.<ref name=\"gma1\"/>\n* March 6 \u2013 The first case of community transmission is reported by the DOH, a 62-year-old Filipino man from nearby [[Cainta]], [[Rizal]], with no known history of travel abroad and who regularly visited a Muslim prayer hall in [[Greenhills (mixed-use development)|Greenhills]], San Juan.\n* March 7 \u2013 [[Taguig]] records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Modesto |first1=Catherine |title=Taguig-based firm says an employee tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/7/Deloitte-employee-coronavirus-positive.html?fbclid=IwAR2eajMCxa0Y6zVSNthbsokVZxfrigXjxrUufx5GA2PRVyMqC429Y77erv0 |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 9 \n** [[Marikina]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Marikina coronavirus cases jump to 5 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1239830/marikina-govt-on-coronavirus-cases |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Pasig]],<ref>{{cite news |title=4 new confirmed coronavirus cases recorded in Metro Manila |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/9/Coronavirus-cases-Quezon-City-Philippines.html |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> and [[Quezon City]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rita |first1=Joviland |title=QC Mayor Joy Belmonte announces confirmed COVID-19 case in the city |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/728862/qc-mayor-joy-belmonte-announces-confirmed-covid-19-case-in-the-city/story/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> each record its first COVID-19 case.\n** The local governments of San Juan, Marikina, and [[Pasay]] order the suspension of classes for all levels amid the announcement of the first case of community transmission in the metropolis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/09/1999216/san-juan-marikina-pasay-suspend-classes-over-covid-19 |title=San Juan, Marikina, Pasay suspend classes over COVID-19 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Servallos, N.J. |date=March 9, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 10\n** President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] order the closure of all schools, colleges, and universities in Metro Manila from March 10 to 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/253912-walang-pasok-duterte-declares-class-suspensions-metro-manila-coronavirus-threat-march-10-14-2020 |title=Duterte suspends classes in Metro Manila March 10\u201314 over coronavirus threat |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Tomacruz, S. |date=March 9, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** The [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority#Metro Manila Council|Metro Manila Council]], consisting of the Metro Manila mayors and headed by chairman [[Danilo Lim]], convene to discuss measures to prevent the spread of the virus as confirmed cases in the region climbed to 33.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/multimedia/photo/03/10/20/metro-mayors-meet-on-local-lockdowns-after-coronavirus-cases-rise |title=Metro mayors meet on local lockdowns after coronavirus cases rise |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Cellona, J. |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 11 \n** [[Caloocan]] records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=One more COVID-19 patient in Tala hospital \u2013 Malapitan |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/11/one-more-covid-19-patient-in-tala-hospital-malapitan/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n** Manila Mayor [[Isko Moreno]] goes into self-quarantine and isolates himself in the [[Manila City Hall]] after arriving from an official trip to [[London]], U.K.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254164-isko-moreno-self-quarantines-manila-city-hall |title=Isko Moreno self-quarantines at Manila city hall |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Talabong, R. |date=March 11, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 12\n** Las Pi\u00f1as records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |title=Las Pi\u00f1as records 1st COVID-19 case |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/12/20/las-pias-records-1st-covid-19-case |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n** President Duterte announces a partial lockdown on Metro Manila, placing the entire Metro Manila under community quarantine for thirty days beginning on March 15. The suspension of classes in all levels in Metro Manila is extended to April 12.<ref name=\"philstar01\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000353/walang-pasok-duterte-suspends-metro-manila-classes-until-april-12 |title=Walang Pasok: Duterte suspends Metro Manila classes until April 12 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Patag, K.J. |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** Incidents of [[panic buying]] are reported across the region, triggered by the president's partial lockdown order.<ref name=\"panic buying\">{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1240902/look-panic-buying-amid-lockdown-fears-in-metro |title=LOOK: Panic-buying amid lockdown fears in Metro Manila |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Marquez, C. |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 13\n** The local chief executives of Caloocan, [[Malabon]], [[Navotas]], and [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]]: [[Oscar Malapitan]], [[Antolin Oreta]], [[Toby Tiangco]], and [[Rex Gatchalian]], respectively, go into self-quarantine after learning they had come into contact with a confirmed coronavirus patient at a March 5 event in Caloocan's [[North Luzon Expressway]]\u2013Harbor Link.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1240982/camanava-mayors-under-quarantine |title=Camanava mayors under quarantine |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Adonis, M. |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** The DOH reports that four COVID-19 patients in the region had died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/qc-state-of-calamity.html |title=Quezon City declares state of calamity amid COVID-19 threat |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=CNN PH staff |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 14 \u2013 [[Mandaluyong]] records its first three COVID-19 cases.<ref name=\"Mandaluyong 1st case\">{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong declares state of calamity over spread of COVID-19 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/16/20/mandaluyong-declares-state-of-calamity-over-spread-of-covid-19 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 15\n** [[Muntinlupa]] records its first COVID-19 case.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa 1st case\">{{cite web |title=Muntinlupa City Declares State Of Calamity Due To COVID-19 Emergency |url=https://www.muntinlupacity.gov.ph/?p=18062 |publisher=City Government of Muntinlupa |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** A total of 56 checkpoints are set up in numerous points of entry to Metro Manila on the first day of the partial lockdown.<ref name=\"partial lockdown\">{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1242619/police-seal-metro-manila-to-fight-virus |title=Police seal Metro Manila to fight virus |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author1=Yamsuan, C.C. |author2=Agoncillo, J.A. |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** Following a directive from the Metro Manila Council and the confirmation of COVID-19 cases, the city mayors of Makati, Manila, Pasig, and San Juan declare a [[State of emergency|state of calamity]].<ref name=\"state of calamity\"/>\n* March 16 \u2013 President Duterte [[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|imposes an enhanced community quarantine]] covering the entire [[Luzon]], including Metro Manila, suspending [[Transportation in the Philippines|mass public transportation]]; restricting land, air, and sea travel; imposing strict home quarantine; and closing most private establishments until April 13.<ref name=\"gazette1\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2020/03/16/memorandum-from-the-executive-secretary-on-community-quarantine-over-the-entire-luzon-and-further-guidelines-for-the-management-of-the-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19-situation/|title=Memorandum from the Executive Secretary On Community Quarantine Over the Entire Luzon and Further Guidelines for the Management of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Situation|date=March 16, 2020|work=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* March 17 \u2013 The Manila bourse becomes the first major market in the world to shut down over coronavirus fears. It suspends trading for two days following a [[2020 stock market crash|global stock market crash]] which saw the main [[Philippine Stock Exchange]] index plunge more than 30 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-16/philippines-shuts-financial-markets-after-virus-spurs-stock-rout |title=Philippines Becomes First Country to Shut Financial Markets Thanks to Virus |publisher=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] |author1=Tu, Lianting |author2=Sayson, Ian C. |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 19 \u2013 Valenzuela records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Valenzuela reports first COVID-19 case |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730416/valenzuela-reports-first-covid-19-case/story/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 23 \u2013 Malabon records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernardo |first1=Jaehwa |title=Malabon records first COVID-19 case |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/23/20/malabon-records-first-covid-19-case |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 24 \u2013 Several private hospitals in Metro Manila report operating at full-capacity due to the pandemic and urged patients to look for alternative hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247913/5-metro-hospitals-reach-full-capacity-for-covid-19-cases |title=5 Metro Manila hospitals reach full capacity for COVID-19 cases |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author1=Yamsuan, C.C. |author2=Yee, J. |date=March 25, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 28\n** Navotas records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Valenzuela |first1=Nikka |title=Navotas records first coronavirus case |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250197/navotas-records-first-coronavirus-case |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n** The [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]], except [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport Terminal 1|Terminal 1]], closes following the suspension of domestic and international flights resulting from travel restriction impositions.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/03/28/2003833/airlines-mount-cargo-only-flights-transport-vital-goods |title=Airlines mount 'cargo-only' flights to transport vital goods |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Mercurio, R. |date=March 28, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]] General Manager Jojo Garcia is confirmed as coronavirus positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/28/2003984/mmda-general-manager-positive-covid-19 |title=MMDA general manager positive for COVID-19 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=San Juan, R. |date=March 28, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 31 \u2013 The [[Philippine National Police]] reports that 10,850 curfew violators have been apprehended across the region since the start of the enhanced community quarantines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1251886/pnp-records-more-than-70k-violators-of-quarantine-protocols |title=Over 70,000 violated Luzon-wide quarantine protocols \u2013 PNP |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Marquez, C. |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n* April 1\n** The local government of Manila reports its largest single-day increase in coronavirus infections so far with 41 new cases, bringing the city's total to 116.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/1/manila-records-largest-single-day-jump-coronavirus-.html |title=City of Manila records largest single-day jump in COVID-19 cases, total now at 116 |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=April 1, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n** More than 800 Filipino repatriates from four virus-stricken cruise ships in the U.S. arrive at the Ninoy Aquino International Airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/256625-filipinos-united-states-cruise-ships-arrive-philippines-april-1-2020 |title=881 Filipinos from cruise ships in U.S. now back in PH |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Tomacruz, S. |date=April 1, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n* April 2\n**The Inter-Agency Task Force on Emerging Infectious Diseases (IATF-EID) announced that Metro Manila remains the worst hit by the coronavirus crisis in the country after 1,511 cases were confirmed in the region, or more than 50 percent of the total confirmed cases in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/02/20/metro-manila-remains-ph-epicenter-of-coronavirus-crisis-galvez |title=Metro Manila remains PH epicenter of coronavirus crisis - Galvez |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Maru, D. |date=April 2, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 inter-agency taskforce spokesman [[Karlo Nograles]] announces the mandatory wearing of [[surgical mask|face mask]]s in public for residents in all regions under enhanced community quarantine in Luzon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/256753-filipinos-luzon-required-wear-face-masks |title=Luzon residents now required to wear face masks when leaving homes |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Tomacruz, S. |date=April 2, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n* April 3 \u2013 The [[National Capital Region Police Office]] confirm its first COVID-19 casualty among its ranks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/04/03/news/latest-stories/2-policemen-succumb-to-virus/709280/ |title=2 policemen succumb to virus |publisher=[[The Manila Times]] |date=April 3, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n*April 6\n**A ten-man medical team from China arrive in Manila to share their experience in prevention and control of the coronavirus disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/04/06/2005737/chinese-coronavirus-doctors-arrive-manila |title=Chinese coronavirus doctors arrive in Manila |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author1=Santos, R. |author2=Brago, P.L. |date=April 6, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Human decontamination|Decontamination]] tents are installed in public hospitals and government offices across the region by the Metropolitan Manila Development Authority.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/06/20/mmda-sets-up-decontamination-tents-in-public-hospitals-govt-offices |title=MMDA sets up decontamination tents in public hospitals, gov't offices |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=April 6, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n*April 7\n**President Duterte approves an extension of the enhanced community quarantine in the region until April 30.<ref name=\"ecqex\"/>\n**The Health department launches a [[24/7 service|24/7]] coronavirus hotline for Metro Manila residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/7/Telemedicine-consultation-COVID.html |title=DOH launches telemedicine consultation for Metro Manila residents |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=April 7, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Embassy of the United States, Manila]] announce the cancellation of all scheduled visa appointments until May 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/08/20/us-embassy-in-manila-all-visa-interviews-until-may-4-cancelled |title=US embassy in Manila: All visa interviews until May 4 cancelled |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=April 8, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n*April 8\n**The [[Rizal Memorial Stadium]] in [[Malate, Manila|Malate]] opens as a 116-bed COVID-19 emergency healthcare facility, with 108 more beds expected to be completed by April 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.inquirer.net/294438/rizal-memorial-stadium-ready-to-accept-initial-116-covid-19-patients |title=Rizal Memorial Stadium ready to accept initial 116 COVID-19 patients |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Abadilla, D.D. |date=April 8, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[World Health Organization]] Western Pacific Regional Office in Manila express its approval of the quarantine measures as it claims it was able to prevent a large-scale community outbreak of the virus in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/8/WHO-PH-lockdown-prevent-large-scale-community-quarantine.html |title=Lockdown saves PH from large-scale community outbreak, WHO says |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=Ferreras, V. |date=April 8, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n*April 11\n**Mass testing begins in [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela City]].<ref name=\"Valenzuela Mass Testing\" />\n*April 14\n**Localized targeted mass testing in the [[Manila|City of Manila]], [[Quezon City]] and [[Muntinlupa]] starts.<ref name=\"MNLQC Mass Testing\" /><ref name=\"Muntinlupa Mass Testing \"/>\n*April 20\n**[[Para\u00f1aque]] starts its own mass testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/19/20/paraaque-to-begin-covid-19-mass-testing-monday-mayor |title=Para\u00f1aque to begin COVID-19 mass testing Monday: mayor |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs|ABS-CBN News]] |date=April 19, 2020 |accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n*April 22\n**Mass testing in [[Mandaluyong]] starts.<ref>{{cite web |title=24 Oras: Mass testing, magsisimula na sa Mandaluyong... |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S7rY4je8r9w |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=April 21, 2020 }}</ref> [[Taguig]] also launched its mass testing with barangay-based, drive-thru facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1262472/taguig-city-sets-up-barangay-based-drive-thru-covid-19-testing |title=Taguig City sets up barangay-based, drive-thru COVID-19 testing |publisher=Inquirer.net |date=April 21, 2020 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n<!-- Please write entries in PRESENT tense. -->\n\n== Response ==\n=== National government ===\n[[File:PNP PRO 3 Checkpoints COVID 19 2.jpg|thumb|Police checkpoint near the northern border of Metro Manila with [[Meycauayan]], [[Bulacan]] in [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]].]]\n[[File:COVID-19 border checkpoint in Muntinlupa.jpg|thumb|Police checkpoint near the southern border of Metro Manila with [[San Pedro, Laguna]] in [[Muntinlupa]].]]\n[[File:Philippine_Airlines_grounded_planes_COVID19.jpg|thumb|Grounded [[Philippine Airlines|PAL]] planes due to halted operations during the lockdown.]]\nBefore the partial lockdown on Metro Manila declared on March 12, President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] had initially suspended classes across all levels in Metro Manila from March 10 to 14 upon reaching a consensus with the [[Metro Manila Council]] (the mayors of Metro Manila) due to the rapidly increasing number of cases especially in the area.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lopez |first1=Virgil |title=Duterte suspends classes in Metro Manila from March 10 to 14, 2020 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/serbisyopubliko/walangpasok/728993/duterte-suspends-classes-in-metro-manila-from-march-10-to-14-2020/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, President Duterte announced a partial lockdown covering Metro Manila, that begun on March 15 and will last until April 14. Under the partial lockdown:<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Ana |title=Ghost town: Manila under coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/manila-turns-ghost-town-coronavirus-lockdown-200315121507679.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Al Jazeera |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* The region is closed to land, air, and sea travel. However, mass transportation within Metro Manila such as the [[Manila Light Rail Transit System|Manila LRT]] and [[Manila Metro Rail Transit System|MRT]] continues to operate under proper [[social distancing]] guidelines.\n* Suspension of classes at all levels in Metro Manila is extended until April 14.\n* Spontaneous and planned mass gatherings are banned.\n* Work in the Executive department is suspended under the lockdown period.\n* The [[Department of Labor and Employment (Philippines)|Department of Labor and Employment]] encourages employers in the private sector to arrange \"flexible work arrangements\".\n\nFollowing the declaration of the partial lockdown, the [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]] (MMDA) suspended the enforcement of the [[Unified Vehicular Volume Reduction Program]], more commonly known as the number coding scheme.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Jel |title=Number coding suspended indefinitely due to 'community quarantine' \u2014 MMDA |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/13/number-coding-suspended-indefinitely-due-to-community-quarantine-mmda/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The Metro Manila Council unanimously approved the imposition of the curfew in a joint resolution. All local governments, except for [[Marikina]] and [[Pateros, Metro Manila|Pateros]], had adopted ordinances imposing the curfew in their respective cities, effective by March 20.<ref>{{cite news |title=LIST: Metro Manila cities with COVID-19 curfew |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/16/Metro-Manila-COVID-19-curfew-list.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> In that joint resolution, the council also ordered the closure of shopping malls and other establishments during the lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cordero |first1=Ted |title=Metro Manila Council wants malls temporarily closed amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729652/metro-manila-council-wants-malls-temporarily-closed-amid-covid-19-threat/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA total of 56 checkpoints were set up to man the borders of Metro Manila on the first day of the partial lockdown.<ref name=\"partial lockdown\"/> At 12 midnight, a total of 26,000 police and military personnel were deployed to contain the pandemic of COVID-19 in the region. Motorists were stopped randomly and asked for their identification along the borders in North Luzon Expressway, [[MacArthur Highway]], and the National Road ([[Maharlika Highway]]). Some checkpoints lacked thermal scanners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254565-metro-manila-lockdown-implementation-checkpoints-march-15-2020 |title=Day 1 of Metro Manila lockdown: Different checkpoints, different rules |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author1=Cupin, B. |author2=Rivas, R. |author3=Tomacruz, S. |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the moratorium on mass public transportation during the enhanced community quarantine, Vice President [[Leni Robredo]] launched free shuttle bus services for those individuals exempted from the quarantine, specifically health professionals, front line government officials, and essential service providers. Robredo's shuttle services travel five routes around Metro Manila, connecting the major hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Robredo donates gear to health workers, pledges free shuttle rides |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/17/robredo-donation-health-workers.html |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Some city governments also deployed such transportation services.\n\nTo address concerns regarding the hoarding and [[panic buying]] of essential goods, some city governments issued ordinances to limit the amount of such goods an individual or establishment could purchase.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa anti-hoarding\">{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa declares state of calamity due to COVID-19 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/muntinlupa-declares-state-of-calamity-due-to-covid-19/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Pasig anti-hoarding\">{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Christia Marie |title=Pasig City OKs anti-hoarding, panic buying ordinance |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243408/pasig-city-anti-panic-buying-ordinance-story |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Valenzuela anti-hoarding\">{{cite news |last1=David |first1=Jun |title=Valenzuela passes anti-hoarding, anti-panic buying measure |url=https://manilastandard.net/index.php/lgu/ncr/319768/valenzuela-passes-anti-hoarding-anti-panic-buying-measure.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Manila Standard |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] has on March 20, 2020 has announced that it has designated three health facilities as COVID-19 referral hospitals namely the [[Philippine General Hospital|UP-Philippine General Hospital]] (UP-PGH) in Manila, the Dr. Jose M. Rodriguez Memorial Hospital and Sanitarium in Caloocan and the [[Lung Center of the Philippines]] in Quezon City. The UP-PGH has stopped admitting non-emergency cases and the Lung Center has dedicated one of its wings of 40 beds for COVID-19 patients. The Philippine Blood Center likewise will not admit any suspected COVID-19 cases with the health department encouraging the public to continue donate blood for COVID-19 patients with critical and severe conditions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galvez |first1=Daphne |title=PGH, 2 other institutions chosen as COVID-19 referral hospitals |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1245731/covid-19-referral-hospitals |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe national government announced on March 25 a cash aid for poor families affected by the pandemic in the region amounting to {{Philippine peso|8,000}} of monthly subsidy over two months as part of the {{Philippine peso|200 billion}} cash assistance program under the [[Bayanihan to Heal as One Act]] signed by President Duterte.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1252020/cash-aid-for-poor-p-8000-in-metro-p-5000-in-regions |title=Cash aid for poor: P8,000 in Metro; P5,000 in regions |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author1=Yap, DJ |author2=Yee, J. |author3=Salaverria, L.B. |date=April 1, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nVice President Robredo converted a [[dormitory]] in [[Quezon City#Cubao|Cubao, Quezon City]], to provide free accommodations for front line health professionals during the enhanced community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Darryl John |title=Robredo launches free dormitory in QC for COVID-19 frontliners |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248747/robredo-launches-free-dormitory-in-qc-for-covid-19-frontliners |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, the [[Department of Agriculture (Philippines)|Department of Agriculture]] launched its first mobile [[farmers' market]] in the region, the ''Kadiwa on Wheels'', in [[Quezon City]], to ensure enough food supply amid the closure of most retail establishments due to the region-wide quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.untvweb.com/news/farm-products-at-cheaper-price-available-at-kadiwa-on-wheels-da/ |title=Farm products at cheaper price available at 'Kadiwa on Wheels' \u2014 DA |publisher=[[UNTV (Philippines)]] |author=Pelayo, M. |date=March 26, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ninoy Aquino Stadium as a COVID-19 quarantine facility.jpg|thumb|The [[Ninoy Aquino Stadium]] in [[Malate, Manila]], reconfigured for use as a quarantine facility.]]\nVarious facilities in the metropolis are being prepared as quarantine sites for less serious COVID-19 cases. Among these are the [[Philippine International Convention Center]], the [[Rizal Memorial Sports Complex]], and the [[World Trade Center Manila|World Trade Center]] will be fully refurbish by April 12. The three facilities alone can accommodate around 2,000 COVID-19 patients. Other non-hospital facilities being considered as possible quarantine sites include the [[PhilSports Complex]], Duty Free Philippines in Para\u00f1aque, [[Amoranto Stadium]], and the [[Quezon Memorial Circle]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Three COVID-19 quarantine facilities in Metro Manila ready by April 12 |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/2/Metro-Manila-quarantine-facility-COVID-19.html |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Local governments ===\n\nOn March 12, the Metro Manila Council reached a consensus to implement city-wide [[curfew]]s from 8{{nbsp}}p.m. to 5{{nbsp}}a.m. the following day to be observed during the enhanced community quarantine, during which only \"essential movements\" for the purchase of essential needs or in cases of emergency are permitted during those hours. Commercial establishments are mandated to suspend operations before the start of the curfew at 8{{nbsp}}p.m.<ref>{{cite news |title=Curfew from 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. to take effect in Metro Manila under COVID-19 quarantine |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/14/20/metro-manila-quarantine-curfew |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> All local governments in Metro Manila have signed into effect ordinances to implement the curfew. The governments of [[Las Pi\u00f1as]],<ref name=\"Las Pi\u00f1as 24-hr\">{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Las Pi\u00f1as City imposes 24-hour curfew |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/21/las-pinas-city-imposes-24-hour-curfew/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> [[Muntinlupa]],<ref name=\"Munti 24-hr\">{{cite news |title=Muntinlupa placed under 24-hour curfew |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/21/muntinlupa-under-24-hour-curfew.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> [[Navotas]],<ref name=\"Navotas 24-hr\">{{cite news |last1=Calalo |first1=Arlie |title=Navotas imposes 24-hour curfew |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/03/23/news/top-stories/navotas-imposes-24-hour-curfew/705072/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> and [[Para\u00f1aque]],<ref name=\"Para\u00f1aque 24-hr\">{{cite news |title=Para\u00f1aque imposes 24-hour curfew |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/23/20/paraaque-imposes-24-hour-curfew |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> however, have since issued ordinances extending the implementation of the curfew to a full 24 hours. \n\nOn April 2, {{abbr|IATF-EID|Inter-Agency Task Force on Emerging Infectious Diseases}} chairman and Cabinet Secretary [[Karlo Nograles]] urged the local governments of Luzon to require residents to wear [[Surgical mask|face mask]]s, [[face shield]]s, or any improvised alternatives while out in public for the duration of the enhanced community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cabico |first1=Gaea Katreena |title=Luzon residents now required to wear face masks outside during lockdown |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/04/02/2005014/luzon-residents-now-required-wear-face-masks-outside-during-lockdown |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> In response, the mayors of [[Malabon]], [[Mandaluyong]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casinas |first1=Jhon Aldrin |title=Mandaluyong imposes fine and imprisonment to violators of face mask ordinance |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/09/mandaluyong-imposes-fine-and-imprisonment-to-violators-of-face-mask-ordinance/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Muntinlupa,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa makes wearing of face masks mandatory |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/02/muntinlupa-makes-wearing-of-face-masks-mandatory/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Para\u00f1aque,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Para\u00f1aque city residents to always wear face masks when in public places, says mayor |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/07/paranaque-city-residents-to-always-wear-face-masks-when-in-public-places-says-mayor/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> [[Pasay]], [[Quezon City]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Wearing of face masks now mandatory in Quezon City |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/7/Quezon-City-face-mask-order-COVID.html |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> and [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]], each issued ordinances to implement the measure within their respective jurisdictions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Agoncillo |first1=Jodee |last2=Ramos |first2=Mariejo |title=Masks now required in Malabon, Valenzuela, QC, Pasay |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1256010/masks-now-a-must-in-malabon-valenzuela-qc-pasay |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> \n\n==== Caloocan ====\n\n[[Caloocan]] Mayor [[Oscar Malapitan]] announced on March 10 the suspension of several scheduled events in the city: the Miss Caloocan Pageant, Mega Job Fairs, City Development Council General Assembly, Outstanding Citizens Awards Night, and Family Day activities, to prevent the spread of the virus among large crowds.<ref name=\"Caloocan, Valenzuela\">{{cite news |last1=Caybyab |first1=Marc Jayson |title=Caloocan, Valenzuela cancel events over COVID-19 |url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/10/1999490/caloocan-valenzuela-cancel-events-over-covid-19 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> On March 24, the city announced that it would impose window hours on residents for the purchase of essential goods. Residents could only access the city's [[Palengke|public markets]] between 6{{nbsp}}a.m. to 9{{nbsp}}a.m. and 4{{nbsp}}p.m. to 7{{nbsp}}p.m., while supermarkets, banks, and pharmacies can only be accessed between 6{{nbsp}}a.m. to 7{{nbsp}}p.m. The city would also issue quarantine passes, permitting only one resident per household between the ages of 18 to 60 years old to leave their house solely for purchasing such goods.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Caloocan gov't imposes window hours for buying basic goods |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247566/caloocan-govt-imposes-window-hours-for-buying-basic-goods |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Las Pi\u00f1as ====\n\nLas Pi\u00f1as Mayor Imelda Aguilar declared a state of calamity in the city on March 14 after a resident was confirmed to have tested positive for COVID-19,<ref>{{cite news |title=Las Pi\u00f1as declares state of calamity amid coronavirus alarm |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/14/20/las-pias-declares-state-of-calamity-amid-coronavirus-alarm |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> and on March 21, the Las Pi\u00f1as government began implementing a 24-hour curfew on its residents.<ref name=\"Las Pi\u00f1as 24-hr\"/> Aguilar has urged lessors to extend rental fees on commercial establishments for at least a month,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Las Pi\u00f1as City mayor asks commercial establishments to waive rental fees for a month |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/21/las-pinas-city-mayor-asks-commercial-establishments-to-waive-rental-fees-for-a-month/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> and also warned suppliers, retailers, and store owners against profiteering from the crisis by overpricing or hoarding essential goods.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Christa Marie |title=Las Pi\u00f1as City warns vs hoarding, profiteering amid coronavirus quarantine |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1249301/las-pinas-city-warns-vs-hoarding-profiteering-amid-coronavirus-quarantine |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2, the Las Pi\u00f1as government reports that more than 75,000 food packages have been distributed to the city's households. Mayor Aguilar urged residents who have yet to receive their packages to contact their ''barangay'' hall.<ref>{{cite news |title=Las Pi\u00f1as assures more food packs coming, appeals for patience |url=https://manilastandard.net/lgu/ncr/321147/las-pi-as-assures-more-food-packs-coming-appeals-for-patience.html |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Manila Standard |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Las Pi\u00f1as government has announced plans to convert a 100-bed drug rehabilitation center in the city into an [[Isolation (health care)|isolation facility]] for its residents suspected or confirmed to have COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Arcilla |first1=Jan |title=Las Pi\u00f1as to convert drug rehab center as isolation area |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/04/03/news/latest-stories/las-pinas-to-convert-drug-rehab-center-as-isolation-area/709283/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Makati ====\n\nIn response to the confirmation of residents of the [[Rockwell Center]] contracting COVID-19, [[Makati]] Mayor [[Abigail Binay]] placed the city under a state of calamity on March 15.<ref name=\"state of calamity\"/> Binay also assured city hall employees that they would continue to receive their salaries amid the enhanced community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Makati gov't employees, contract workers to get paid during lockdown |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255354-makati-govt-employees-salaries-lockdown-coronavirus |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, the Makati government launched free shuttle bus services for doctors, nurses, and other employees of the Ospital ng Makati, which runs between the hospital and certain points in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Cathrine |title=Makati gov't deploys buses for OsMak, city hall employees |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243764/makati-govt-deploys-buses-for-osmak-city-hall-employees |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> In addition, Mayor Binay announced that tricycle drivers affected by the moratorium would receive an initial {{Philippine peso|2,000|link=yes}} (US$39.23) financial assistance to cover the first two weeks of the quarantine. Binay added that a similar financial compensation would be given to jeepney drivers of the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Cathrine |title=Makati to give P2,000-financial aid to city's tricycle drivers |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1244295/makati-to-give-p2000-to-citys-tricycle-drivers-as-financial-aid |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> That same day, the Makati government also announced plans to purchase 5,000 COVID-19 test kits from the [[National Institutes of Health (Philippines)|National Institutes of Health]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zurbano |first1=Joel |title=Makati to procure 5k coronavirus test kits |url=https://manilastandard.net/mobile/article/319887 |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Manila Standard |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Makati Friendship Suites on March 25 was converted into an isolation facility by the city government to accommodate at most 100 patients suspected of COVID-19 and is equipped with [[x-ray machine]]s, [[defibrillator]]s, and [[cardiac monitor]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Layug |first1=Margaret Claire |title=Makati converts hotel into isolation facility for COVID-19 PUIs |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/731239/makati-converts-hotel-into-isolation-facility-for-covid-19-puis/story/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Makati government announced on March 28 that [[single parent]]s in the city \"affected by the enhanced community quarantine\" would receive a one-time financial assistance of {{Philippine peso|1,000}} ($19.81) each. Mayor Binay also announced that public school students, persons with disabilities, and senior citizens would also receive financial assistance from the government.<ref>{{cite news |title=Makati gives cash aid to solo parents amid Luzon lockdown |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/28/20/makati-gives-cash-aid-to-solo-parents-amid-luzon-lockdown |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Malabon ====\n\nOn March 18, Malabon Mayor [[Antolin Oreta]] ordered the city government to provide {{Philippine peso|520,000}} ($10,252.26) to each ''barangay'' for the provision of food during the Luzon-wide enhanced community quarantine. Oreta also ordered the provision of {{Philippine peso|6 million}} ($118,156.44) to the city's ''carinderia'' (food stall) owners for them to provide meals for 300 people every day for 15 days.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=Malabon City gov't releases food budget to barangays for needy residents |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/malabon-city-govt-releases-food-budget-to-barangays-for-needy-residents/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> That same day, he called on [[Maynilad Water Services]] to divert the unused [[Water supply and sanitation in the Philippines|water supply]] of closed malls and other commercial establishments to residential areas.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=Malabon mayor asks water concessionaires to divert mall water supply to residential areas amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/malabon-mayor-asks-water-concessionaires-to-divert-mall-water-supply-to-residential-areas-amid-covid-19-threat/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Oreta endorsed all households in Malabon to the social amelioration program of the [[Department of Social Welfare and Development]] (DSWD) mandated in the [[Bayanihan to Heal as One Act]], saying that \"COVID-19 spares no one, rich or poor.\" The DSWD had allotted packages for only 44,032 households in the city, but the [[Philippine Statistics Authority]] reported in 2015 that 86,000 households comprise the population of Malabon.<ref>{{cite news |title='Rich and poor': Malabon mayor to endorse all families to DSWD for aid |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/02/20/rich-and-poor-malabon-mayor-to-endorse-all-families-to-dswd-for-aid |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Mandaluyong ====\n\nThe [[Mandaluyong]] city council passed an ordinance on March 16 declaring the city under a state of calamity, after reporting three COVID-19 patients, six persons under investigation, and 125 persons under monitoring in the city.<ref name=\"Mandaluyong 1st case\"/>\n\nOn March 17, Mandaluyong Mayor [[Carmelita Abalos]] ordered the release of the [[thirteenth salary]] pay to all of the city's government employees.<ref name=\"13th-month pay\">{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong, Manila gov't employees to get early 13th-month, midyear pay during community quarantine |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/17/mandaluyong-city-hall-13th-month.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Abalos stated that around 100,000 bags of relief goods would be distributed [[door-to-door]] to households in Mandaluyong.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong to deliver food aid for COVID-19 lockdown 'door-to-door' by weekend |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/18/20/mandaluyong-to-deliver-food-aid-for-covid-19-lockdown-door-to-door-by-weekend |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Manila ====\n\n[[File:Philippine General Hospital COVID-19 ward.jpg|thumb|A ward dedicated to COVID-19 patients at the [[Philippine General Hospital]] in [[Ermita]], [[Manila]].]]\n\n[[Manila]] Mayor [[Isko Moreno]], following a directive from the Metro Manila Council, declared a state of calamity in the city on March 15 after the second and third COVID-19 cases were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254621-manila-state-calamity-new-confirmed-coronavirus-cases |title=Manila under state of calamity as city confirms 2 new coronavirus cases|publisher=[[Rappler]] |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Modular Tent Home for Street Dwellers Manila COVID19 1.jpg|thumb|right|A gymnasium in Manila converted into a temporary homeless shelter during the region-wide community quarantine.]]\nThe Manila Department of Social Welfare (MDSW) on March 16 began rescuing [[street people]], [[pavement dwellers]], and other homeless people, as well as people living outside the city who were unable to retreat home following the imposition of the Luzon-wide enhanced community quarantine. They took refuge at the Delpan Sports Complex in [[Tondo, Manila|Tondo]]. The city allocated {{Philippine peso|227.5 million}} ($4.45 million) from the its budget to assist families affected by the quarantine. MDSW Chief Re Fugoso ordered the lockdown of the Manila Boys Town Complex and the Manila Youth Reception Center in [[Ermita]] for the protection of the children and teenagers residing there amid the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tiangco |first1=Minka |title=Street dwellers given food, shelter by Manila City government |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/street-dwellers-given-food-shelter-by-manila-city-government/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Likewise Mayor Moreno on March 18 ordered all lodging facilities in Manila to provide free accommodations for front line health workers, such as doctors and nurses, throughout the Luzon-wide enhanced community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Talabong |first1=Rambo |title=Isko Moreno orders Manila hotels, motels to house health workers for free |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255062-isko-moreno-order-hotels-motels-manila-house-health-workers-for-free |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> On March 17, Mayor Moreno drafted a resolution ordering the release of the mid-year bonuses of the city's government employees. He also drafted another resolution appropriating funds for the city's job order and [[Endo contractualization|contractualized workers]].<ref name=\"13th-month pay\"/>\n\nOn March 19, the city deployed 189 [[Electric bicycle#Tricycles|electric tricycles]] to exclusively transport front line health workers to the city's public hospitals. Non-health workers would not be serviced in observance of the moratorium on mass public transportation; however, drivers of electric tricycles would receive salaries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Maria Angelica |title=Manila to deploy 189 e-trikes for COVID-19 frontliners |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730444/manila-to-deploy-189-e-trikes-for-covid-19-frontliners/story/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The city also coordinated with the [[Department of Social Welfare and Development]] of the national government in sourcing food supplies for the city's families. Mayor Moreno has stressed that the city could only produce between 8,000 and 11,000 food packs, but would not suffice for the city's 350,000 families. As of March 25, the city had already provided for about 39,000 families.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Merez |first1=Arianne |title=Isko Moreno appeals for food supplies for Manila |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/25/20/isko-moreno-appeals-for-food-supplies-for-manila |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> On April 5, Isko Moreno signed an ordinance enacting the city's amelioration fund. The city allocated {{Philippine peso|591 million}} ($12 million) for around 568,000 families, distributing {{Philippine peso|1,000}} ($19.73) to each household.<ref>{{cite news |title=Manila City to give P1,000 cash grant to more than 500,000 families |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/05/20/manila-city-to-give-p1000-cash-grant-to-more-than-500000-families |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Mayor Isko Moreno launched an [[Survey data collection#Online survey|online survey]] via his [[Facebook]] page inquiring Manila residents about their health status in relation to COVID-19 and their recent travel history. [[PLDT]], one of the country's major telecommunications providers, assisted the city government in providing enhanced data connectivity for the online survey service. PLDT also assisted in augmenting the hotline facility at the [[Manila City Hall]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hilario |first1=Edgard |title=Manila City Hall launches city-wide COVID-19 health survey |url=https://technology.mb.com.ph/2020/03/23/manila-city-hall-launches-city-wide-covid-19-health-survey/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, the [[Manila City Council]] approved an ordinance penalizing [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|discriminatory acts]] directed against coronavirus patients and other patients under evaluation, including discrimination of health workers on the basis of their medical condition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/03/manila-passes-ordinance-vs-covid-19-stigmatization/ |title=Manila passes ordinance vs COVID-19 stigmatization |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |author=Pedrajas, J.A. |date=April 3, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The following day on April 4, Mayor Moreno ordered the temporary closure of the Ospital ng Sampaloc (Sampaloc Hospital) after five hospital staff contracted the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/4/manila-hospital-closes-staff-coronavirus-positive.html |title=Manila hospital to temporarily close after staff test positive for COVID-19 |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=April 4, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>  On April 6, Mayor Moreno announced that he and several other government officials in the city would donate their salaries to the [[Philippine General Hospital]] to increase its financial capability amid the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mendoza |first1=John Eric |title=Isko, Manila officials donate salaries to PGH |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/04/06/news/top-stories/isko-manila-officials-donate-salaries-to-pgh/710131/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Manila government partnered with the [[Department of Agriculture (Philippines)|Department of Agriculture]] to launch the ''Kadiwa Rolling Store'' project, a mobile [[farmers' market]] that sells fresh products to residents amid the closure of retail establishments due to the enhanced community quarantine. The first unit was deployed to [[Santa Ana, Manila|Santa Ana]] on April 6.<ref>{{cite web |title=NEWS ALERT: Kadiwa rolling stores to kick off in Manila amid COVID-19 crisis |url=http://manila.gov.ph/2020/04/news-alert-kadiwa-rolling-stores-to-kick-off-in-manila-amid-covid-19-crisis/ |publisher=City Government of Manila |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, the City of Manila announced that it is now capable of conducting localized mass targeted testing for COVID-19. The six city-owned district hospitals and the Delpan Quarantine Facility each can take up to 232 tests a day, which is capable of producing up to 1,624 swab tests weekly.<ref name=\"MNLMassTestingAnnouncement\">{{cite web |title=Manila City to begin mass COVID-19 testing |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/13/Manila-City-COVID-19-mass-testing.html |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> On the same day, the city placed Barangay 20 in Tondo on total lockdown for 24 hours, because its residents had been conducting leisurely activities such as boxing, gambling and cockfighting despite the Luzon-wide lockdown.<ref>{{cite web |title=Barangay in Manila placed under 'total shutdown' due to boxing, gambling while on lockdown |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/13/20/barangay-in-manila-placed-under-total-shutdown-due-to-boxing-gambling-while-on-lockdown |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs|ABS-CBN News]] |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |date=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lalu |first1=Gabriel Pabico |title=Isko places Manila's Barangay 20 under 24-hour shutdown for holding bingo, boxing games |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1258011/manilas-barangay-20-on-shutdown-due-to-violation-of-quarantine-regulations |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |website=Inquirer.net |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 19, Mayor Isko Moreno confirmed that Sampaloc, Manila will be placed on lockdown. The district has the most number of cases in the city, with 98 confirmed COVID-19 patients and 158 suspected cases.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sampaloc, Manila to be placed on lockdowns |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/19/mayor-confirms-sampaloc-manila-will-be-placed-on-lockdown.html?fbclid=IwAR2z4ESaF_sNjyIccIFCR1J8iK1QAwEG5WrTYiArCT8JHkRyeKdNh6vQEh8?fbclid=lwAR2 |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Marikina ====\n[[File:Marikina Mayor Teodoro inspects COVID-19 testing center (March 23, 2020).jpg|thumb|Mayor [[Marcelino Teodoro]] inspects a proposed [[COVID-19 testing]] center in [[Marikina]], March 23]]\n\n[[Marikina]] Mayor [[Marcelino Teodoro]] on March 16 announced that his government would install misting and decontamination tents across numerous public spaces in the city.<ref name=setup>{{cite news |last1=Casinas |first1=Jhon Aldrin |title=Marikina City to set up lab testing center for the detection of COVID-19 cases |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/14/marikina-city-to-set-up-lab-testing-center-for-the-detection-of-covid-19-cases/}}</ref> The Marikina government pledged to provide households with free disinfectant solutions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Madarang |first1=Catalina Ricci |title=Marikina City, MMDA step up efforts vs COVID-19 with disinfection tents |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/trends-spotlights/2020/03/16/164301/marikina-mmda-covid19-disinfection-tents/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the moratorium on mass public transportation during the Luzon-wide enhanced community quarantine, the Marikina government launched on March 18 free shuttle bus services to ferry front line health professionals from across the city to its hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ornedo |first1=Julia Mari |title=Marikina adds more routes to free ride service for residents amid quarantine |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730277/marikina-adds-more-routes-to-free-ride-service-for-residents-amid-quarantine/story/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Marikina government announced plans to set up a COVID-19 testing center. On March 16, Mayor Teodoro announced that around 3,000 testing kits would be procured and the government would partner with Manila Health Tek and the [[National Institutes of Health (Philippines)|Philippine National Institutes of Health]], to test \"[[Patient Under Investigation|patients under investigation]]\" (PUIs) and \"patients under monitoring\" (PUMs) for COVID-19.<ref name=setup/> Field testing was scheduled to begin on March 24. The procurement of a {{Philippine peso|2.7 million}} ($53,222.42) [[polymerase chain reaction]] machine specifically for testing, along with 3,000 test kits worth {{Philippine peso|4 million}} ($78,824.72) was also announced by the city government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Panti |first1=Llanesca |title=Marikina sets up lab, buys equipment to give free COVID-19 tests |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730475/marikina-to-provide-free-covod-19-testing-to-health-workers-persons-at-risk/story/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>  \n\nOn March 26, Mayor Teodoro reported that the {{abbr|DOH|Department of Health}} rejected the usage of the city government's COVID-19 testing center because of its location, which had to be in a \"separate free-standing building\", but was located inside the Marikina City Health Office. Teodoro claimed that their testing center had met all the other criteria for a testing center and he even offered to cede its full operation to the DOH.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ornedo |first1=Julia Mari |title=DOH rejected COVID-19 testing center, Marikina mayor says |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/731398/doh-rejected-covid-19-testing-center-marikina-mayor-says/story/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> However, the DOH refuted the mayor's claims that they had rejected the usage of the testing center.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health dept denies rejecting Marikina's COVID-19 test lab |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/26/20/health-dept-denies-rejecting-marikinas-covid-19-test-lab |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Nevertheless, Teodoro said that his government would relocate its testing center.<ref name=\"Marikina\">{{cite news |last1=Ayalin |first1=Adrian |title=Marikina to transfer COVID-19 testing center to separate building to comply with DOH requirements |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/27/20/marikina-to-transfer-covid-19-testing-center-to-separate-building-to-comply-with-doh-requirements |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The new location is an unoccupied building in [[Barangays of Marikina#Concepcion I (Uno)|Concepcion Uno]], which has yet to be accredited by the DOH as a testing center in order to operate.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marikina finds new location for planned COVID-19 testing center |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/30/Marikina-new-location-COVID-19-testing-center.html |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> On April 7, Teodoro announced that testing for COVID-19 would be free for the city's residents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ornedo |first1=Julia Mari |title=Marikina to make COVID-19 testing free for residents |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/733077/marikina-to-make-covid-19-testing-free-for-residents/story/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> On April 15, he announced plans to open the testing center even without the approval of the DOH, saying that his government \"can no longer put off mass testing for Marikina residents\" and is prepared to face any charges.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Arcangel |first1=Xianne |title=Marikina mayor ready to face charges for launching COVID-19 testing lab without DOH permit |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/15/marikina-mayor-tedoro-ready-to-face-charges-covid-lab.html |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Marikina government designated the defunct Marikina Hotel to serve as an isolation facility for PUMs.<ref name=\"Marikina\"/>\n\nOn April 6, the Marikina City Health Office launched a [[telehealth]] medical consultation program via [[VSee]] for residents with concerns related to COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ayalin |first1=Adrian |title=Marikina launches online consultation for COVID-19 concerns |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/06/20/marikina-launches-online-consultation-for-covid-19-concerns |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Muntinlupa ====\n[[File:Muntinlupa Mayor Jaime Fresnedi oversees COVID-19 relief operations (March 20, 2020).jpg|thumb|[[Muntinlupa]] Mayor [[Jaime Fresnedi]] oversees relief operations by the city government, March 20]]\n[[File:COVID-19 curfew violators in Muntinlupa.jpg|thumb|Violators of the curfew are detained by city officials in Muntinlupa, March 24]]\n\n[[Muntinlupa]] Mayor [[Jaime Fresnedi]] organized a COVID-19 task force on March 10. He ordered schools and government facilities in the city to be disinfected.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa\">{{cite news |author1=[[Ignacio Bunye|Bunye, Ignacio]] |title=Muntinlupa City's response to coronavirus \u2013 a timeline |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/23/muntinlupa-citys-response-to-coronavirus-a-timeline/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Fresnedi ordered Muntinlupa ''barangay'' officials to identify residents with recent travel history for monitoring. He also ordered officials to install isolation facilities to accommodate suspected cases of COVID-19; the city government assembled a [[field hospital]] outside the Ospital ng Muntinlupa, which became fully operational on March 18. Police officials were deployed to prevent students from entering malls, following the suspension of classes in Metro Manila.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa\"/>\n\nMayor Fresnedi placed the city under a state of calamity on March 16, after confirming its first COVID-19 case.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa 1st case\"/> The Muntinlupa city council approved four ordinances in relation to addressing the pandemic: the first is to prevent the hoarding and panic buying of essential goods; the second is to prohibit the sale, distribution, and consumption of alcoholic beverages during the duration of the Luzon-wide enhanced community quarantine; the third is to order the closure of all private establishments in the city, except for those providing essential goods such as supermarkets, pharmacies, and banks; and the fourth is to restrict the operation of restaurants, ''carinderias'', and other eateries to [[take-out]] only.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa anti-hoarding\"/> Fresnedi ordered the advanced release of the thirteenth salary pay of the city hall's employees.<ref name=\"MB\">{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa ready to provide food assistance up to 4 months |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/20/muntinlupa-ready-to-provide-food-assistance-up-to-4-months/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Muntinlupa government launched free shuttle services for front line workers based in the city, deploying [[Jeepney#E-jeepneys|electric jeepneys]].<ref name=\"Muntinlupa\"/> \n\nA Barangay Captain in Muntinlupa, on March 19, ordered the lockdown of an undisclosed subdivision in [[Alabang]] following confirmation from the DOH that two confirmed COVID-19 cases in the city are residents of that subdivision.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa City gov't to intensify community quarantine measures |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/19/muntinlupa-city-govt-to-intensify-community-quarantine-measures/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Muntinlupa government distributed 1,500 food packages in [[Poblacion, Muntinlupa|Poblacion]] on March 20, which the government claimed covered about 70 percent of the city's population. Mayor Fresnedi assured the city's residents that the city government will provide food assistance to the city's \"vulnerable households\" that would last for up to three to four months.<ref name=\"MB\"/> The government plans to distribute 94,847 more food packages to other households, targeting at least 85 percent of the city's population.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa to distribute 94,847 food packs in 2nd wave of assistance |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/07/muntinlupa-to-distribute-94847-food-packs-in-2nd-wave-of-assistance/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, Mayor Fresnedi signed an ordinance to impose a 24-hour city-wide curfew, superseding the 8{{nbsp}}p.m. to 5{{nbsp}}a.m. curfew.<ref name=\"Munti 24-hr\"/>\n\nOn March 24, the Muntinlupa city council passed an ordinance to convert the Ospital ng Muntinlupa into a COVID-19 testing facility. The government would procure polymerase chain reaction machines and testing kits. The city already houses the [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] in Alabang, one of the medical facilities accredited by the DOH to perform COVID-19 testing in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa wants to establish own COVID-19 testing center |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/24/muntinlupa-wants-to-establish-own-covid-19-testing-center/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Two days later, the council passed an ordinance to extend the payment deadlines for real [[property tax]] and [[corporate tax]] until three months after the original deadline. Mayor Fresnedi also urged lessors of commercial establishments and residential units in the city to extend the payment of rental fees, in consideration of the closure of business establishments during the quarantine period.<ref>{{cite web |title=Munti LGU extends RPT and Business Tax Payment, asks lessors to waive rental fees |url=https://www.muntinlupacity.gov.ph/?p=18193 |publisher=City Government of Muntinlupa |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Muntinlupa city council, on April 7, passed an ordinance to grant around 60,000 scholars in the city the advanced release of their allowances for the second quarter of the academic year, in response to the \"financial impact\" of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rita |first1=Joviland |title=60,000 Muntinlupa scholars to receive allowances in advance amid COVID-19 impact |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/733012/60-000-muntinlupa-scholars-to-receive-allowances-in-advance-amid-covid-19-impact/story/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Navotas ====\n\nPrior to President Duterte's declaration of a partial lockdown on Metro Manila, [[Navotas]] Mayor [[Toby Tiangco]] had already suspended classes at all levels in the city for March 9 as a preventive measure against the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mendoza |first1=Red |title=Navotas suspends classes due to Covid-19 outbreak |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/03/07/news/latest-stories/navotas-suspends-classes-due-to-covid-19-outbreak/700948/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> Tiangco also appealed to the [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]] to pass all students in the city for the school year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Navotas mayor asks DepEd to pass all students; Duque says class suspension not a good idea now |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/728716/navotas-mayor-asks-deped-to-pass-all-students-duque-says-class-suspension-not-a-good-idea-now/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, the Navotas city council issued an ordinance limiting the amount of work required for its government officials to work 10 hours per day for four days, effective March 16, in observance of social distancing guidelines.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navotas to implement 4-day work week for some LGU offices, employees |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/13/20/navotes-4-day-work-week-due-to-covid-19-coronavirus |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe Navotas government, on March 22, began distributing around 18,000 food packs to the city's [[Slums in Metro Manila|informal settlers]] living in \"danger zones\" and families listed under the city's housing projects.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Paunan |first1=Jerome Carlo |title=Navotas uses 'katok' system for family food pack delivery amid quarantine |url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036876 |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |agency=Philippine Information Agency |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> \n\nMayor Tiangco announced on March 23 that the city's government employees would receive {{Philippine peso|6,000}} ($117.41) each as compensation, totaling {{Philippine peso|6.4 million}} ($125,233.22). Tiangco also announced that their quarterly bonus payment would be released in advance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navotas releases P6.4 million for cash aid to employees amid lockdown |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255698-navotas-city-releases-budget-fund-incentives-employees-coronavirus |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> That same day, Tiangco issued an executive order to implement a 24-hour curfew in the city.<ref name=\"Navotas 24-hr\"/> \n\nThe Navotas government converted a [[vocational education]] facility in the city into a temporary shelter for the medical staff of the Navotas City Hospital attending to COVID-19 patients.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navotas provides free shelter for city's medical frontliners |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/256319-navotas-city-free-shelter-medical-frontliners-novel-coronavirus |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Navotas government announced on April 9 that it would distribute packages of [[amlodipine]], [[losartan]], [[metformin]], and [[simvastatin]] to the city's senior citizens.<ref>{{cite news |title=Senior citizens of Navotas City to be provided with maintenance meds at home |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/09/20/senior-citizens-of-navotas-city-to-be-provided-with-maintenance-meds-at-home |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Para\u00f1aque ====\n\n[[Para\u00f1aque]] Mayor Edwin Olivarez declared the city under a state of calamity on March 16 due to the rise of COVID-19 cases in nearby areas.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Darryl John |title=COVID-19: Para\u00f1aque City placed under state of calamity |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243108/covid-19-paranaque-city-placed-under-state-of-calamity |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Olivarez later declared a \"total lockdown\" on the city, prohibiting visitors \"without official business\" from entering the city's premises during the Luzon-wide enhanced community quarantine. The \"total lockdown\" permits only front line offices and basic services providers to operate throughout its duration. He also requested city hall employees to go on leave.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Para\u00f1aque City implements 'total lockdown' |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/paranaque-city-implements-total-lockdown/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Mayor Olivarez announced that the city's front line workers, which he identified specifically as medical personnel, drug store personnel, health workers, supermarket employees, bank personnel, [[business process outsourcing]] personnel, restaurant personnel, and city government employees, would be provided with free transportation to their different workplaces.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Para\u00f1aque City provides free transportation for city's frontliners, essential workers |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/19/paranaque-city-provides-free-transportation-for-citys-frontliners-essential-workers/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> That same day, Mayor Olivarez announced that both regular and contractualized employees in Para\u00f1aque would receive their full mid-year bonuses, in addition to a {{Philippine peso|6,000}} ($117) clothing allowance until March 23.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abad |first1=Roderick |title=Para\u00f1aque City Hall workers get midyear bonus amid lockdown |url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2020/03/19/paranaque-city-hall-workers-get-midyear-bonus-amid-lockdown/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=BusinessMirror |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy March 21, the Para\u00f1aque government had distributed around 100,000 relief goods to 14,000 \"vulnerable households\" across the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Para\u00f1aque City gov't to distribute relief goods house-to-house to vulnerable sectors |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/20/paranaque-city-govt-to-distribute-relief-goods-house-to-house-to-vulnerable-sectors/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Para\u00f1aque government began imposing a 24-hour curfew to its residents from March 24.<ref name=\"Para\u00f1aque 24-hr\"/> The following day, a photo published by the [[San Isidro, Para\u00f1aque|San Isidro]] government circulated on social media showing alleged curfew violators in the ''barangay'' being forced to sit under the sun as penalty. Netizens have criticized the action for physical torture.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Talabong |first1=Rambo |title=LOOK: In Para\u00f1aque, curfew violators sit under the sun as punishment |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255645-barangay-san-isidro-paranaque-curfew-violators-punished-sit-under-sun-curfew |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Olivarez, on April 7, signed Executive Order No. 2020-027, which protects front liners and COVID-19 patients, including PUIs and PUMs, from [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|any acts of discrimination]] in the city during the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Arcilla |first1=Jan |title=Para\u00f1aque protects frontliners, patients |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/04/07/news/national/paranaque-protects-frontliners-patients/710592/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Pasay ====\n[[Pasay]] Mayor Emi Calixto-Rubiano declared the city under a state of calamity on March 16 due to \"the extremely high incidence of COVID-19 cases in the city.\" On March 18, she ordered the advanced release of the thirteenth salary pay of city hall employees, in accordance with President Duterte's call for local government units to do so.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nazario |first1=Dhel |title=Pasay City mayor orders early release of 13th month pay, salaries of city hall employees |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/pasay-city-mayor-orders-early-release-of-13th-month-pay-salaries-of-city-hall-employees/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Pasay government announced on March 19 that it had collaborated with the [[Department of Trade and Industry (Philippines)|Department of Trade and Industry]] to deploy [[food cart]]s to roam around the city's 201 ''barangays'' and sell essential goods such as food and medicines, in order to limit the movement of its residents during the Luzon-wide enhanced community quarantine. The Pasay government also announced that it collaborated with the [[Philippine Army]] to provide free transportation for Pasay-based health professionals and other service front liners who work outside the city, as well as persons with disabilities and senior citizens, amid the moratorium on public transportation; the government procured 100 electric tricycles and 20 [[Mitsubishi Delica|Mitsubishi L300]] vans.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Cathrine |title=DTI to launch 'rolling stores' in Pasay amid quarantine |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1245125/pasay-rolling-stores-during-quarantine |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, the Pasay government ordered the installation of modular tents at the Pasay City Sports Complex and the Padre Burgos Elementary School to serve as [[Isolation (health care)|isolation units]] for COVID-19 PUIs in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Pasay sports complex, school transformed into isolation rooms for PUIs |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247741/pasay-govt-on-isolation-units-for-puis |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Pasig ====\n[[File:Pasig Mayor Vico Sotto meets with COVID-19 doctors (March 20, 2020).jpg|thumb|Pasig Mayor [[Vico Sotto]] (second from the right) attends a briefing with doctors from [[The Medical City]] in response to the COVID-19 pandemic, March 20]]\n[[File:Mobile market in Pasig.jpg|thumb|A \"mobile ''[[palengke]]''\" in operation in [[Pasig]] during the quarantine.]]\n\nFollowing the confirmation of COVID-19 patient at [[The Medical City]] in the city's district of [[Ortigas Center|Ortigas]] on March 9, [[Pasig]] Mayor [[Vico Sotto]] ordered city officials to implement the guidelines of the DOH and the [[World Health Organization]] in preventing the spread of the virus, including contact tracing, organizing response teams, disinfecting public spaces, and the cancellation of all public events and gatherings.<ref name=\"Sotto\">{{cite news |last1=Abellon |first1=Bam |title=Here's everything that Mayor Vico Sotto has done so far in response to COVID-19 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/ancx/culture/spotlight/03/20/20/heres-everything-that-mayor-vico-sotto-has-done-so-far-in-response-to-covid-19 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Around 500 sets of [[personal protective equipment]] were distributed by city government on March 14 to its 30 ''barangays''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guzman |first1=Jimmyley |title=Sprayers, protective equipment distributed to Pasig barangays |url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036318 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |publisher=Philippine Information Agency |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Sotto approved the declaration of a state of calamity in Pasig on March 15 after six confirmed cases and one fatality were recorded in the city. The mayor also announced that they have ordered a mandatory isolation for the health workers of Rizal Medical Center after they were exposed to a confirmed coronavirus patient.<ref name=\"state of calamity\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/16/2001178/more-cities-metro-manila-under-state-calamity |title=More cities in Metro Manila under state of calamity |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Servallos, N.J. |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Pasig City Council on March 16 approved an anti-panic buying and hoarding of essential goods ordinance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bigtas |first1=Jannielyn Ann |title=Pasig City to implement anti-panic buying, hoarding ordinance |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729913/pasig-city-to-implement-anti-panic-buying-hoarding-ordinance/story/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Sotto appealed to the [[Department of Interior and Local Government]] (DILG) on March 17 to allow the operation of [[Motorized tricycle (Philippines)|tricycles]] and the city's bus service to specifically transport front line health professionals and other essential service providers to the city's hospitals during the quarantine period, following the moratorium on mass public transportation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vico Sotto rejects ban on tricycles in Pasig City amid Luzon lockdown |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/vico-sotto-rejects-ban-on-tricycles-in-pasig-city-amid-luzon-lockdown |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pasig City sets up sanitation tents outside hospitals, provides bus service for healthcare workers |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/lifestyle/healthandwellness/730259/pasig-city-sets-up-sanitation-tents-outside-city-hall-pcgh-children-s-hospital/story/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Sotto had earlier raised tricycles fares by 50 percent following the decline in residents leaving their homes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=Vico Sotto temporarily allows tricycles in Pasig for people reporting to work amid quarantine |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/17/164402/vico-sotto-temporarily-allows-tricycles-in-pasig-for-people-reporting-to-work-amid-quarantine/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Tricycle drivers were mandated by the city government to transport a maximum of three passengers per ride in observance of the national government's social distancing guidelines.<ref name=\"Sotto\"/>\n\nOn March 18, Mayor Sotto pledged to give both [[Endo contractualization#Regular employment|regular]] and contractualized government employees their full salaries during the duration of the enhanced community quarantine in Luzon, while emergency front line workers would receive hazard and overtime pays.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Pasig City Hall employees, from regular to contractual ones, to get full salaries amid enhanced quarantine |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730108/pasig-employees-to-get-full-salaries-hazard-pay-amid-enhanced-quarantine/story/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The Pasig government also assembled sanitation tents at the entrances of the city hall and two hospitals, prepared food packages containing vitamins to be distributed to the city's \"vulnerable households\",<ref name=\"Sotto\"/> and purchased three [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|octocopter drones]] to be utilized for disinfecting public spaces.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=Vico Sotto has been stellar with his proactive COVID-19 initiatives, and Filipinos want him to lead the whole country |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/18/164558/vico-sotto-has-been-stellar-with-his-proactive-covid-19-initiatives-and-filipinos-want-him-to-lead-the-whole-country/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Sotto ordered the Dahlia Hotel in the city on March 19 to be converted into a quarantine facility able to accommodate at least 300 PUMs and PUIs with mild to moderate symptoms of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Sotto\"/> That same day, the DILG rejected Mayor Sotto's appeal on operating tricycles in Pasig claiming it violates the national government's directives to observe social distancing measures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reysio-Cruz |first1=Matthew |title=Vico Sotto defends tricycle proposal amid DILG objection |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1245279/sotto-defends-tricycle-proposal-amid-dilg-objection |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The Pasig government responded by commissioning two electric-powered City Optimized Managed Electric Transport jeeps to transport the city's front line workers across Pasig to its hospitals.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Reyes |first1=Kate |title=Check out Pasig's earth-friendly rides for hospital frontliners |url=https://www.spin.ph/life/cars-and-tech/pasig-city-to-provide-earth-friendly-rides-to-hospital-frontliners-a2442-20200319 |website=Spin.ph |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe deadlines of all tax payments, rent, permits, and other obligatory submissions were extended on March 24 by the city government for two months.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kabagani |first1=Lade Jean |title=Deadline of tax payments, other gov't fees extended in Pasig City |url=http://www.canadianinquirer.net/2020/03/25/deadline-of-tax-payments-other-govt-fees-extended-in-pasig-city/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |via=Philippine Canadian Inquirer |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> \n\nFive trucks were deployed by the Pasig government on March 25 transporting loads of essential goods, such as food, to different ''barangays'' in the city, where they are sold to residents. The government labeled these trucks as \"mobile ''[[palengke]]s''\", aimed at limiting the movement of people during the community quarantine. The essential goods sold to residents through the trucks are sourced from the vendors of the city's public markets \"to assist them generate income.\" About 400,000 food packs were also distributed by the city government to Pasig residents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kabagani |first1=Lade Jean |title=Pasig City's 'mobile palengke' boosts social distancing |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1097797 |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe Pasig government also began giving the city's jeepney, tricycle, and [[UV Express]] drivers financial assistance of {{Philippine peso|3,000}} ($59) each for a total of {{Philippine peso|55.5 million}} ($1.1 million) starting March 30.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Laurel |first1=Drei |title=Thousands of Pasig City PUV drivers to get P3,000 financial aid starting next week |url=https://www.topgear.com.ph/news/motoring-news/pasig-city-puv-financial-assistance-a962-20200326 |website=Top Gear Philippines |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, the [[National Bureau of Investigation (Philippines)|National Bureau of Investigation]] (NBI) probed Mayor Sotto for allegedly violating the [[Bayanihan to Heal as One Act]] by allowing tricycles to transport the city's front line workers despite the moratorium on public transportation during the period of the enhanced community quarantine. The following day, Sotto sent a letter to the NBI seeking for clarification.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Vico Sotto replies to NBI, asks for clarification |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1253184/vico-sotto-replies-to-nbi-asks-clarification |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> He claimed that his alleged violation occurred [[Ex post facto law|before the law had been enacted]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Vico Sotto 'confident nothing will happen' in NBI probe |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/04/05/20/vico-sotto-confident-nothing-will-happen-in-nbi-probe |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Sotto announced through a [[Facebook]] post on April 9 that the Pasig government would shoulder the expenses for the cremation of the city's residents who died from complications of the coronavirus disease.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casinas |first1=Jhon Aldrin |title=Pasig to pay for cremation of COVID-19 fatalities |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/09/pasig-to-pay-for-cremation-of-covid-19-fatalities/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Quezon City ====\n[[File:COVID-19 Swab Booth QC (April 7, 2020).jpg|thumb|A COVID-19 swab booth is installed at the Quezon City General Hospital.]]\n\nOn March 13, [[Quezon City]] Mayor [[Joy Belmonte]] announced a state of calamity for the city following six confirmed cases of local COVID-19 transmissions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Quezon City declares state of calamity amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/qc-state-of-calamity.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> She immediately placed 11 ''barangays'' under \"extreme enhanced community quarantine\", prohibiting its residents from exiting their respective ''barangays''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zembrano |first1=Chiara |title=QC enforces 'extreme enhanced community quarantine' in areas with COVID-19 cases |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/18/20/quezon-city-lockdown-extreme-enhanced-community-quarantine-due-to-covid-19-coronavirus |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> The [[Quezon City University]] has been used as a quarantine site for PUIs in the city. As of March 24 at least 379,000 food packs has been distributed to residents by the Quezon City government.<ref name=\"covidqcnow72\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19 cases in QC now at 72; four die, one recovers |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/731197/covid-19-cases-in-qc-now-at-72-four-die-one-recovers/story/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Quezon City government partnered with [[Hotel Sogo]] and the Rainbow Place Dormitory in [[Quezon City#Tandang Sora|Tandang Sora]] to provide free accommodations for service front liners, especially health professionals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tuquero |first1=Loreben |title=Quezon City provides free lodging for health workers |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255986-quezon-city-free-lodging-health-workers-coronavirus |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, the Quezon City government imposed an executive order prohibiting the sale, purchase, and consumption of alcoholic beverages in public places during the enhanced community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Christia Marie |title=QC imposes liquor ban until end of Luzon-wide quarantine |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1249257/qc-imposes-liquor-ban-until-end-of-luzon-wide-quarantine |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Quezon City government announced on April 4 that it would fund the efforts of the [[Philippine Red Cross]] to assemble mobile testing centers in the city to conduct \"mass testing\" on its residents. As of April 7, Quezon City has more COVID-19 cases than any other city in Metro Manila.<ref>{{cite news |title=Philippine Red Cross acquires machines, special ambulances to aid in fight vs coronavirus |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/04/20/philippine-red-cross-acquires-machines-special-ambulances-to-aid-in-fight-vs-coronavirus |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chavez |first1=Chito |title=PH Red Cross chooses QC as first COVID-19 mobile testing site |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/04/ph-red-cross-chooses-qc-as-first-covid-19-mobile-testing-site/ |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, Mayor Belmonte signed an executive order penalizing any act of discrimination against persons suspected or confirmed to have the coronavirus, as well as front liners and their families.<ref>{{cite news |title=QC gov't passes ordinance punishing acts of discrimination amid COVID-19 pandemic |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/733278/qc-gov-t-passes-ordinance-punishing-acts-of-discrimination-amid-covid-19-pandemic/story/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrototype COVID-19 swab test booths designed by the [[Philippine Institute of Civil Engineers]] were installed at the Quezon City General Hospital on April 7. The booths are designed to minimize the exposure of health workers on PUIs and PUMs being tested for the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mateo |first1=Janvic |title=Quezon City General Hospital installs swab booths for COVID testing |url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/04/09/2006466/quezon-city-general-hospital-installs-swab-booths-covid-testing |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== San Juan ====\n\nOn March 6, the [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]] government ordered the temporary closure of a Muslim prayer hall at the [[Greenhills Shopping Center]] after a frequent visitor of the pay hall was reported as the country's fifth case of confirmed COVID-19 diagnosis. San Juan Mayor [[Francis Zamora]] also ordered the postponement of all scheduled public events in the city.<ref>{{cite news |title=San Juan prayer hall frequented by coronavirus patient temporarily closed |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/6/san-juan-muslim-prayer-hall-coronavirus.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Zamora announced on March 15 that the villages of [[Greenhills (mixed-use development)|Greenhills]] and West Crame were identified as coronavirus hotspots after four salon workers in Greenhills tested positive for the virus. Zamora thus declared a state of calamity in the city and ordered the temporary closure of all malls in the city, as well as all churches.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casinas |first1=Jhon Aldrin |title=Zamora: Malls in San Juan City temporarily closed starting March 15; curfew ordinance to follow |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/14/zamora-malls-in-san-juan-city-temporarily-closed-starting-march-15-curfew-ordinance-to-follow/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, Mayor Zamora announced that the San Juan government had reached an agreement with [[Xavier School]] to convert the San Juan City Science High School into a 100-bed isolation facility for COVID-19 PUIs in the city. Xavier School would assist the government in providing necessary medical equipment, medicines, and front line personnel.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=San Juan City to use public high school building as quarantine facility |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248832/san-juan-city-to-use-high-school-building-as-quarantine-facility |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, Mayor Zamora signed an ordinance prohibiting the sale, distribution, and consumption of alcoholic beverages during the quarantine period.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bajo |first1=Anna Felicia |title=San Juan, Caloocan implement liquor ban |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/731972/san-juan-city-implements-liquor-ban/story/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Taguig ====\n\n[[File:COVID-19 disinfection at Bonifacio Global City (April 9, 2020).jpg|thumb|Taguig officials disinfecting the streets of the [[Bonifacio Global City]].]]\n\n[[Taguig]] Mayor [[Lino Cayetano]] ordered a lockdown on the city on March 17 after four of its residents tested positive for COVID-19; the lockdown only permits delivery vehicles of basic goods and supplies to enter and exit Taguig.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taguig placed on lockdown to prevent coronavirus spread |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/lockdown-taguig-coronavirus-cvoid-19-community-quarantine |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The city government collaborated with transportation groups and ''barangays'' to organize [[Premium Point-to-Point Bus Service|point-to-point transportation services]] for its residents to access basic supplies amid the moratorium on mass public transportation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taguig City on lockdown starting Wednesday amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/17/Taguig-City-lockdown-Wednesday-COVID-19.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Mayor Lino warned ''barangay'' officials against collecting payment fees while issuing the city's health professionals and other essential workers special permits to freely roam around the city at any time during the Luzon-wide enhanced community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Jel |title=Mayor Cayetano stops money collection of barangays for travel permit |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/21/mayor-cayetano-stops-money-collection-of-barangays-for-travel-permit/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> During the enhanced community quarantine, health workers from the Taguig health office had been distributing [[condom]]s, [[birth control pill]]s, [[Tuberculosis management|medication for tuberculosis]] and [[HIV medication|HIV]], and vitamins for [[hypertension]] and [[diabetes]] to residents for free.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Sex in the time of COVID-19: Taguig City gives pills, condoms to residents |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248796/sex-in-the-time-of-covid-19-taguig-city-gives-pills-condoms-to-residents |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> On March 28, the Taguig government launched [[Telehealth|telemedicine]] consultation services for its residents to lessen mobility during the quarantine period.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Arcilla |first1=Jan |title=Remote medical consultations launched in Taguig |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/03/28/news/latest-stories/remote-medical-consultations-launched-in-taguig/707459/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, the city began distributing health kits, which includes [[vitamin C]] and a coronavirus information brochure, to the city's senior citizens and those with underlying health conditions. The government also plans to distribute around 2,000 grocery packs door-to-door to the city's households in order to limit the movement of people.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Caliwan |first1=Christopher Lloyd |title=Taguig prioritizes elderly, sick in distribution of health kits |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1097156 |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> On March 30, the Taguig city government announced that around 15,000 members of accredited jeepney, tricycle, and pedicab operators and drivers associations in the city would receive a subsidy of {{Philippine peso|4,000}} ($79.24). Some tricycles drivers have offered to transport front liners around the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Agoncillo |first1=Jodee |title=Taguig public transport drivers to get P 8K subsidy |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250657/taguig-public-transport-drivers-to-get-p-8k-subsidy |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe city has converted a hostel at the [[Technological University of the Philippines]], the Hagonoy Sports Complex, the Taguig City Disability and Development Center, the Taguig Lakeshore Hall in [[New Lower Bicutan]], and a building in Ibayo Tipas, into isolation facilities for COVID-19 patients in case the Taguig\u2013Pateros District Hospital reaches its maximum capacity.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Arcilla |first1=Jan |title=Taguig converts 5 facilities as isolation areas |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/04/04/news/latest-stories/taguig-converts-5-facilities-as-isolation-areas/709555/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAmid reports that some residents of the [[Bonifacio Global City]] have been jogging and leisurely walking outside their homes, Mayor Cayetano warned on April 9 that \"authorities will not hesitate to arrest\" residents who engage in outdoor activities during the enhanced community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Caliwan |first1=Christopher Lloyd |title=BGC residents warned vs. outdoor activities amid ECQ |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1099371 |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Valenzuela ====\n\nOn March 13, the [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]] city council approved an ordinance prohibiting the hoarding and panic buying of essential goods.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Anti-hoarding, anti-panic buying ordinance to be implemented in Valenzuela |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729483/anti-hoarding-anti-panic-buying-ordinance-to-be-implemented-in-valenzuela/story/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nValenzuela Mayor [[Rex Gatchalian]] announced on March 15 the cancellation of several scheduled events, namely the Top Taxpayers and Top Job Providers\u2019 Night and Concert, Mega Job Fair, and the weekend Family Day activities in public schools, to prevent the spread of the virus amongst large crowds.<ref name=\"Caloocan, Valenzuela\"/> Gatchalian placed the city under a state of calamity, the following day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Valenzuela City placed under state of calamity amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/16/20/valenzuela-city-placed-under-state-of-calamity-amid-covid-19-threat |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Gatchalian announced on March 17 that {{Philippine peso|500\u2212700}}-worth of vouchers would be issued to some 75,000 Valenzuela\u00f1o families for which they could use to claim essential goods at groceries.<ref>{{cite news |title=Valenzuela City to issue food vouchers during Luzon lockdown |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/03/19/20/valenzuela-city-to-issue-food-vouchers-during-luzon-lockdown |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The city's government would also distribute food packages to families registered under the [[conditional cash transfer]] program.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baron |first1=Gabriela |title=Valenzuela to distribute food packs to citizens at risk of poverty |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/valenzuela-to-distribute-food-packs-to-citizens-at-risk-of-poverty/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> He assured the city's health professionals that they would be issued special permits for easier entry into the city borders, amid the establishment of checkpoints in accordance with the national government's directives regarding the partial lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=Mayor Gatchalian assures health workers of easy entry into Valenzuela despite Luzon quarantine |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/mayor-gatchalian-assures-health-workers-of-easy-entry-into-valenzuela-despite-luzon-quarantine/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Valenzuela government established two centralized isolation centers on March 19 to accommodate suspected cases of COVID-19 and confirmed patients.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Valenzuela sets up isolation centers vs. COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730438/valenzuela-sets-up-isolation-centers-vs-covid-19/story/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The government also designated a dormitory in the city for medical workers from [[Obando, Bulacan]], who could not return home due to the lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Maria Angelica |title=Valenzuela opens dorm for health workers residing in locked down Obando, Bulacan |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/732859/valenzuela-opens-dorm-for-health-workers-residing-in-locked-down-obando-bulacan/story/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, the Valenzuela city council passed an ordinance prohibiting the sale, distribution, and consumption of alcoholic beverages during the enhanced community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hallare |first1=Katrina |title=Valenzuela imposes liquor ban during enhanced community quarantine period |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248511/valenzuela-imposes-liquor-ban-during-enhanced-community-quarantine-period |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, the Valenzuela government partnered with the Valdeco Greenleaf Market to launch a mobile market system. Mayor Gatchalian said that he was inspired by the Pasig government's \"mobile ''palengke''\" initiative and sought Pasig Mayor Vico Sotto's permission. The government utilized electric tricycles, instead of trucks like in Pasig, to suit the city's smaller terrain roads.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Laurel |first1=Drei |title=Valenzuela City launches own mobile market during COVID-19 quarantine |url=https://www.topgear.com.ph/news/motoring-news/valenzuela-city-mobile-market-covid-19-a962-20200328 |website=Top Gear Philippines |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe Valenzuela government has reportedly [[Automation|automated]] its [[contact tracing]] system.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reyes |first1=Bernadette |title=Valenzuela automates COVID-19 contact tracing procedures |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/731759/valenzuela-automates-covid-19-contact-tracing-procedures/story/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Valenzuela government partnered with [[The Medical City]] to provide free \"mass testing\" for COVID-19 to the city's residents, starting April 11.<ref name=\"Valenzuela Mass Testing\">{{cite news |last1=Cerrudo |first1=Aileen |title=Valenzuela City to begin mass testing for COVID-19 on April 11 |url=https://untvweb.com/news/valenzuela-city-to-begin-mass-testing-for-covid-19-on-april-11/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=UNTV |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> The public-private partnership deal, which Mayor Gatchalian noted was the first in the country to provide COVID-19 \"mass testing\", was signed on April 4. Gatchalian stated his government would be responsible for the purchase and supply of the test kits, while the laboratory tests and the analysis and interpretation of results would be conducted by The Medical City.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cator |first1=Currie |title=Valenzuela joins hands with The Medical City for mass testing |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/4/valenzuela-city-mayor-the-medical-city-mass-testing-coronavirus.html |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Aside from TMC, they are also partnering with Detoxicare Molecular Diagnostics Laboratory to expedite the testing processes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rita |first1=Joviland |title=Valenzuela City eyes zero backlog in COVID-19 testing by Saturday|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/734093/valenzuela-city-eyes-zero-backlog-in-covid-19-testing-by-saturday/story/ |accessdate=April 15, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Management ==\n\n=== Face masks and respiratory hygiene ===\n\nOn April 2, the IATF-EID declared that wearing face masks will be mandatory over the entire Luzon, including Metro Manila. Residents are now required to wear surgical masks, do-it-yourself masks, handkerchiefs, or improvised cloth that covers the nose and mouth at all times, amid the shortage of available face masks globally. Local government units are urged to issue necessary executive orders or ordinances to require the use of face mask and impose penalties for offenders.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Parrocha |first1=Azer |title=Use of face masks now required in all areas under ECQ |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1098595 |work=Philippine News Agency |date=April 2, 2020 |access-date=April 15, 2020 }}</ref> Earlier, Muntinlupa had already passed an ordinance requiring its residents to wear face masks on March 30,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa makes wearing of face masks mandatory |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/02/muntinlupa-makes-wearing-of-face-masks-mandatory/ |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 2, 2020 |access-date=April 15, 2020 }}</ref> followed by Makati on April 13.<ref>{{cite news |title=Makati City requires wearing face masks in public places |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/257798-makati-city-requires-wearing-face-masks-public-places-coronavirus |work=Rappler |date=April 13, 2020 |access-date=April 15, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== Mass testing ===\n\nThe first localized COVID-19 mass testing began on [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]] on April 11, which was administered for free to susceptible and probable residents, front line health workers and returning overseas Filipinos. On April 13, the [[Manila]] city government announced its capability to conduct its own localized targeted mass testing, which can produce up to 1,624 tests per week.<ref name=\"MNLMassTestingAnnouncement\" />\n\nOn April 14, the [[Manila|City of Manila]], [[Quezon City]] and [[Muntinlupa]] began their own localized mass testing.<ref name=\"MNLQC Mass Testing\">{{cite news |last1=Crisostomo |first1=Shiela |title=COVID mass testing begins in Metro Manila today |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/04/14/2007170/covid-mass-testing-begins-metro-manila-today |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |work=[[Philippine Star|PhilStar Global]] |website= |date=April 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Mariejo S. |last2=Valenzuela |first2=Nikka G. |title=Mass testing in Metro Manila under way |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1257199/mass-testing-in-metro-under-way |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer|Inquirer.net]] |date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Muntinlupa Mass Testing\">{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/14/muntinlupa-starts-covid-19-mass-testing-of-puis/?__cf_chl_jschl_tk__=d348ec7394fd9f29cf3961870fa281919cad3616-1587261452-0-AWGhh7XLoHp1yAJOtVV61XDixfeQlptrL1onF0fylXthtS4dfSny-zMsSjCa_X0Iiimj9y0gAMhZZsdLb1PKe7An8Q3323XbEGhlO7TvHvk_rTlBjswpxtpJMueStIIM_3UeGh7Disw6cOeu73ppElI7h1WZbuthRBUockPHZ8q0Ji5nwNb0xyxKTmux6RE6RlEZcqJXCSDIJfb8hAxdHLivsLpV7nTpZgNl5iz8Hi5TDB_JTQy5OiSyossxrPrSFHH7oDmZixe2YTPxeTlun3ZO5xEqnaQbPghaZgXewzm9f1XDZfl7NrrWQwvUJqbVMdT6rD6Lgjj-LkypaRpdfZex_jeAs89U_juljOr2oQDI |title=Muntinlupa starts COVID-19 mass testing of PUIs |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |date=April 14, 2020 |accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Testing facilities ====\n\nThere are 11 accredited testing facilities within Metro Manila by the national government. The cities of Marikina and Muntinlupa are also planning to set up their own testing centers.<ref name=marikinadohdefers>{{cite news |last1=Servallos |first1=Neil Jayson |title=DOH defers COVID testing in Marikina |url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/24/2002972/doh-defers-covid-testing-marikina |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"muntinlupatesting\">{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa wants to establish own COVID-19 testing center |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/24/muntinlupa-wants-to-establish-own-covid-19-testing-center/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* [[Armed Forces of the Philippines Medical Center]] \u2013 Quezon City\n* Detoxicare Molecular Diagnostics Laboratory \u2013 Mandaluyong\n* [[Lung Center of the Philippines]] \u2013 Quezon City\n* [[Makati Medical Center]] \u2013 Makati\n* [[University of the Philippines Manila|UP Manila]] [[National Institutes of Health (Philippines)|National Institutes of Health]] \u2013 Manila\n* [[Philippine Red Cross]] \u2013 Mandaluyong\n* [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] \u2013 Muntinlupa\n* [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] \u2013 Manila\n* [[St. Luke's Medical Center \u2013 Global City]] \u2013 Taguig\n* [[St. Luke's Medical Center \u2013 Quezon City]] \u2013 Quezon City\n* [[The Medical City]] \u2013 Pasig\n\n== Impact ==\n[[File:Podium Mall coronavirus sign warning.jpg|thumb|A coronavirus warning sign at the entrance of [[The Podium]] mall in [[Ortigas Center]], [[Mandaluyong]].]]\n=== Crime and disobedience ===\n\nOn March 22, the [[Philippine National Police]] (PNP) reported that [[Crime in the Philippines|crime rates in Metro Manila]] decreased by almost 70 percent, according to data between March 15 to 20 during the implementation of the partial Metro Manila lockdown and the Luzon-wide enhanced community quarantine. During that period, the PNP reported only seven cases of murder, ten cases of homicide, 11 cases of physical injury (compared to 41 last year), five cases of rape (compared to 23 last year), 18 cases of robbery (compared to 50 last year), and 24 cases of theft (compared to 68 last year). The PNP attributed the decline in crime rates to the implementation of strict home quarantine measures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rucuenco |first1=Aaron |title=Crime rate down by 70% in Metro Manila, 77.3% in Central Luzon due to lockdown |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/22/crime-rate-down-by-70-in-metro-manila-77-3-in-central-luzon-due-to-lockdown/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 21 protesters in Quezon City were arrested for organizing a rally \"without government permit.\" The protesters claimed that the Quezon City government failed to provide them basic necessities, especially food, during the quarantine; the Quezon City government denied the claims. The city's mayor, [[Joy Belmonte]], ordered the release of the protesters \"in the interim for humanitarian reasons\" and issued them a warning instead. The PNP stated that it would file charges against the protesters as mass gatherings are prohibited under the enhanced community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=21 protesters demanding food aid arrested in Quezon City |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/1/quezon-city-protesters-arrested-.html |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Senator [[Francis Pangilinan]] announced that he, his wife [[Sharon Cuneta]], and their daughter would shoulder the {{Philippine peso|15,000}} ($296.57) bail for each of the arrested protesters. Actress [[Jodi Sta. Maria]] stated that she would also contribute to the bail.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Terrazola |first1=Vanne Elaine |title=Pangilinan et al bail out protesters detained for staging QC rally |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/04/pangilinan-et-al-bail-out-protesters-detained-for-staging-qc-rally/ |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Economy ===\n\nBeing the economic hub of the Philippines, the Metro Manila economy comprises 38.1% of the country's [[gross domestic product]]. The imposition of President Duterte's partial lockdown on the region on March 16 and the [[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|enhanced community quarantine on Luzon]] that superseded it [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines#Economy|impacts heavily on the Philippine economy as a whole]]. [[Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas]] Governor [[Benjamin Diokno]] and [[National Economic and Development Authority]] Director-General [[Ernesto Pernia]] forecast that, due to the imposition of the enhanced community quarantine on Luzon, contractions in the national economic growth would likely be experienced in the second and third quarters of the year. Diokno and Pernia stated that, consequently, the Philippines would likely enter a [[recession]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Noble |first1=Luz Wendy |last2=Laforga |first2=Beatrice |title=PHL may go into recession \u2014 Diokno |url=https://www.bworldonline.com/phl-may-go-into-recession-diokno/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=BusinessWorld |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>  \n\nFollowing the partial lockdown on Metro Manila, incidents of [[panic buying]] and hoarding were reported and became widespread across the region. This prompted most local governments to issue anti-hoarding and panic buying ordinances.<ref name=\"panic buying\"/>\n\nSevere congestion at the [[Port of Manila]] was reported on March 30 after the region was placed under lockdown with many unclaimed food cargoes and overstaying containers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/business/256372-ictsi-says-food-cargo-stuck-manila-port-coronavirus-lockdown |title=Food cargo stuck at Manila port due to coronavirus lockdown \u2013 ICTSI |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Rivas, R. |date=March 30, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\n\nOn March 12, classes were suspended in Metro Manila until April 12 when President Rodrigo Duterte raised the status of the COVID-19 pandemic in the whole Philippines to \"Code Red Sub-Level 2\" as part of a partial lockdown<!-- common term for 'community quarantine' --> measure on Metro Manila.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729459/code-red-sub-level-2-duterte-announces-tougher-measures-vs-covid-19-threat/story/|title=Code Red Sub-Level 2: Duterte announces 'community quarantine' vs. COVID-19|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=GMA News Online|url-status=live|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/12/COVID-19-Metro-Manila-restrictions-Philippines.html|title=Duterte declares lockdown of Metro Manila for 30 days due to COVID-19|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=[[CNN Philippines]]|url-status=live|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The class suspensions were later extended up to April 14 through a memorandum circular released by Malaca\u00f1ang on March 14.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729643/classes-canceled-in-metro-manila-until-april-14-2020-due-to-covid-19-threat/story/|title=Classes canceled in Metro Manila until April 14, 2020 due to COVID-19 threat|date=March 14, 2020|work=|accessdate=March 16, 2020|url-status=live|publisher=GMA News|website=GMA News Online}}</ref>\n\nThe extension of the enhanced community quarantine prompted the [[Ateneo de Manila University]] to shorten its semester and pass all its students, automatically promoting them. The university announced that students would receive a refund of {{Philippine peso|20,000}} ($395.75) from their tuition fees.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bigtas |first1=Jannielyn |title=Ateneo shortens semester; students to receive tuition refund, passing mark amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/733053/ateneo-shortens-semester-students-to-receive-tuition-refund-passing-mark-amid-covid-19-threat/story/ |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Entertainment ===\n\nOn March 13, the {{abbr|MMDA|Metropolitan Manila Development Authority}} announced a postponement of the 1st [[Metro Manila Summer Film Festival]] as a result of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/03/13/20/summer-mmff-postponed-after-metro-manila-put-under-community-quarantine |title=Summer MMFF postponed after Metro Manila put under 'community quarantine' |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> The [[Philippine Amusement and Gaming Corporation]] ordered the suspension of all gaming operations in Metro Manila, including the land-based casinos in [[Entertainment City]] and [[Newport City, Metro Manila|Newport City]], on March 15. The gaming regulator also announced that they were limiting the operations of [[Philippine offshore gaming operation]]s in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/03/15/20/pagcor-suspends-casino-gaming-operations-during-metro-manila-quarantine |title=PAGCOR suspends casino, gaming operations during Metro Manila quarantine |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Environment ===\n\nThe [[Department of Environment and Natural Resources]] (DENR) reported that the [[air quality index]] of different cities in Metro Manila had improved, following the implementation of the enhanced community quarantine on Luzon. The cities with the lowest amounts of inhalable [[PM10|coarse particulate matter]] (PM<sub>10</sub>) were Para\u00f1aque (7), Marikina (9), San Juan (17), Malabon (22), Taguig (32), and Pasay (43), all reporting \"good\" values of air quality; meanwhile, the cities of Pasig (53), Makati (54), Las Pi\u00f1as (86), and Northern Caloocan (92) all reported \"moderate/fair\" values. The DENR collected the data after photos surfaced on social media depicting [[smog]]-free skylines of some of the aforementioned cities, which is likely a result of minimized activity due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Laurel |first1=Drei |title=DENR data shows improved air quality in Metro Manila due to quarantine |url=https://www.topgear.com.ph/news/motoring-news/denr-air-quality-metro-manila-a962-20200325 |website=Top Gear Philippines |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Medical facilities ===\n\nBy March 26, eight [[List of hospitals in Metro Manila|private hospitals in Metro Manila]] announced that it had reached its maximum capacity to handle any COVID-19-related case. These hospitals were namely the [[Asian Hospital and Medical Center]] in [[Alabang]], Muntinlupa;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Damicog |first1=Jeffrey |title=Asian Hospital declares full capacity |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/26/asian-hospital-declares-full-capacity/ |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> [[Chinese General Hospital and Medical Center]] in [[Santa Cruz, Manila]]; [[De Los Santos Medical Center]] in Quezon City; [[Makati Medical Center]] in Makati; Marikina Valley Medical Center in Marikina; [[The Medical City]] in [[Ortigas Center]], Pasig; and both hospitals of [[St. Luke's Medical Center]] in [[St. Luke's Medical Center \u2013 Quezon City|Quezon City]] and [[St. Luke's Medical Center \u2013 Global City|Bonifacio Global City]], Taguig.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yamsuan |first1=Cathy Ca\u00f1ares |last2=Yee |first2=Jovic |title=5 Metro Manila hospitals reach full capacity for COVID-19 cases |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247913/5-metro-hospitals-reach-full-capacity-for-covid-19-cases |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=With a heavy heart, two more Metro Manila hospitals stop admission of COVID-19 patients as they reach 'full capacity' |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/25/165031/with-a-heavy-heart-two-more-metro-manila-hospitals-stop-admission-of-covid-19-patients-as-they-reached-full-capacity/ |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=More major Metro Manila hospitals declare full capacity, shut to COVID-19 patients |url=https://coconuts.co/manila/news/more-major-metro-manila-hospitals-declare-full-capacity-shut-to-covid-19-patients/ |website=Coconuts Manila |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Private firms ===\n\nOn March 11, the [[Wack Wack Golf and Country Club]] in Mandaluyong temporarily closed after one of its guests, a Singaporean permanent resident, was confirmed to have contracted COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong golf club shut after guest tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/11/coronavirus-sanitation-wack-wack-golf-club.html |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/exclusive-philippine-golf-club-on-lockdown-after-guest-from-singapore-tests-positive | title=Philippine golf club on lockdown after Singapore guest tests positive for coronavirus| date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the MMDA's imposition of an area-wide curfew during the Metro Manila lockdown, mall operators [[Ayala Malls]], [[SM Supermalls]], [[Robinsons Malls]], and [[Vista Malls]] initially announced that it would shorten the operating hours of its malls in Metro Manila, from 11{{nbsp}}a.m. to 7{{nbsp}}p.m., in response.<ref>{{cite news |title=Metro Manila malls to shut down early ahead of quarantine |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/03/14/20/metro-manila-quarantine-malls-to-shut-down-early-ahead-of-quarantine |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> However, Metro Manila city governments later passed ordinances mandating the temporary closure of malls with the exception of establishments providing essential goods and services (such as supermarkets, pharmacies, and banks) from March 16 \"until further notice\", in accordance with the joint resolution passed by the Metro Manila Council regarding the lockdown.<ref>{{cite web |title=UPDATED: Which NCR malls are closed and which cities have curfew? See list |url=https://www.spin.ph/life/active-lifestyle/possible-mall-closures-eyed-as-ncr-goes-into-curfew-starting-tomorrow-a1374-20200314 |website=Spin.ph |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, food delivery services [[Grab (company)|GrabFood]] and [[Foodpanda]] resumed operations in the region after a temporary suspension due to quarantine restrictions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/business/2020/3/17/Grab-Philippines-car-GrabFood-suspended-coronavirus.html |title=GrabFood, FoodPanda resume food delivery services amid Luzon quarantine |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nGrabWheels, an [[electric scooter]] rental service of the ridesharing company [[Grab (company)|Grab]], was activated to service health workers in select cities in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.mb.com.ph/2020/04/01/grabwheels-activated-for-health-workers/ |title=GrabWheels activated for health workers |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |author=Abadilla, E.V. |date=April 1, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Religious sector ===\n\nOn March 14, the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Manila]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Cubao|Diocese of Cubao]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Novaliches|Diocese of Novaliches]], and the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Para\u00f1aque|Diocese of Para\u00f1aque]] announced that it would suspend the celebration of [[Mass in the Catholic Church|Masses]] and other public gatherings, including all [[Holy Week]] activities, in all its churches \"until further notice\", in an effort to curb the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Catholic churches in Metro Manila suspend masses |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/No-masses-Manila-archdiocese-churches-COVID-19.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, the [[National Commission on Muslim Filipinos]] announced on March 16 a temporary suspension of all Islamic gatherings in the region in response to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/16/2001412/islamic-religious-activities-metro-manila-other-areas-under-covid-19-quarantine-temporarily-suspended |title=Islamic religious activities in Metro Manila, other areas under COVID-19 quarantine temporarily suspended |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Cabico, G.K. |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports ===\n\nTop collegiate Metro Manila competitions, the [[NCAA Season 95|National Collegiate Athletic Association]] and the [[UAAP Season 82|University Athletic Association of the Philippines]], cancelled all its remaining games.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yumol |first1=David Tristan |title=NCAA cancels remainder of Season 95 due to COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/sports/2020/3/19/NCAA-season-95-cancelled-coronavirus.html |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Escarlote |first1=Mark |title=UAAP Board cancels Season 82 |url=https://sports.abs-cbn.com/uaap/news/2020/04/07/uaap-board-cancels-season-82-67509 |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN Sports |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> National leagues largely held in Metro Manila such as the [[2020 PBA season|Philippine Basketball Association]], [[2020 Philippines Football League|Philippines Football League]], and the [[2020 PSL season|Philippine Super Liga]] were postponed.<ref name=listleagues>{{cite news |last1=Cabildo |first1=Leigh Nald |title=LIST: Philippine leagues suspended amid coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/other-sports/254350-list-philippine-leagues-suspended-coronavirus-outbreak?utm_medium=Social&utm_source=Twitter#Echobox=1584069791 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=PFF And PFL Statement \u2013 Postponement Of Philippines Football League Season 2020 |url=http://pff.org.ph/2020/03/13/pff-and-pfl-statement-postponement-of-philippines-football-league-season-2020/ |publisher=Philippine Football Federation |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Marikina Mayor [[Marcelino Teodoro]] also announced the cancellation of the [[2020 Palarong Pambansa]] as host city of the games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2020/03/10/marikina-calls-off-palaro/ |title=Marikina calls off Palaro |publisher=[[BusinessMirror]] |author=Bonilla, R.R.C. |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Transportation ===\n\nBy March 14, a mass exodus to the provinces was observed in the hours leading to the Metro Manila lockdown, following its announcement two days prior. Thousands were seen flocking to the provincial bus terminals such as the [[Araneta City Bus Port]] in Quezon City as well as the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254503-photos-mass-exodus-metro-manila-lockdown-coronavirus |title=IN PHOTOS: Mass exodus before Metro Manila 'lockdown' |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Rey, A. |date=March 14, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Motorcycle ridesharing companies [[Angkas]] and Joyride suspended their Metro Manila services on March 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/15/angkas-joyride-suspend-operations-in-metro-manila-but-deliveries-continue/ |title=Angkas, Joyride suspend operations in Metro Manila, but deliveries continue |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |author=Ramos, M. |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident Duterte's March 16 declaration of a month-long enhanced community quarantine on the island of Luzon, including Metro Manila, suspended the operations of all modes of [[public transportation in Metro Manila]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=San Juan |first1=Alexandria Dennise |title=Operation of all modes of public transportation in Luzon suspended \u2013 DOTr |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/operation-of-all-modes-of-public-transportation-in-luzon-suspended-dotr/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The [[Metro Rail Transit Corporation]] and [[Light Rail Transit Authority]] suspended the operations of the [[Manila Metro Rail Transit System]] and the [[Manila Light Rail Transit System]], respectively, from March 17; [[Manila Light Rail Transit System Line 1|LRT Line 1]] would resume operations on April 12, while [[Manila Metro Rail Transit System Line 3|MRT Line 3]] would lift its suspension on April 13.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jazul |first1=Noreen |title=MRT, LRT announce temporary suspension of operations |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/mrt-lrt-announce-temporary-suspension-of-operations/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> However, with the extension of the lockdown until April 30, the resumption of rail transport within the region is likely postponed.\n\nOn March 28, the Manila International Airport Authority announced the temporary closure of all terminals of the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]] except [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport Terminal 1|Terminal 1]] following the suspension of domestic flights and international travel restrictions due to the pandemic and subsequent lockdown.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n=== Treatment of workers ===\n\nOn April 8, 170 construction workers in [[Pasay]] had been reportedly stranded in their barracks since the implementation of the enhanced community quarantine on March 17. They claimed that they were given only {{Philippine peso|1,000}} ($19.82) from their employer, who \"abandoned\" them, and had to \"resort to begging to buy food.\" The Pasay government responded by distributing relief goods to the workers. According to Pasay Mayor Emi Calixto-Rubiano, the employer had pledged to provide food and other essentials to the workers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Maria Angelica |title=Construction workers stranded in Pasay due to quarantine resort to begging |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/733242/construction-workers-stranded-in-pasay-due-to-quarantine-resort-to-begging/story/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=900\n|colors= #FF6347, #FFC000, #87CEEB, #000000\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x= Mar 6, Mar 8, Mar 9, Mar 10, Mar 11, Mar 12, Mar 13, Mar 14, Mar 15, Mar 16, Mar 17, Mar 18, Mar 19, Mar 20, Mar 21, Mar 22, Mar 23, Mar 24, Mar 25, Mar 26, Mar 27, Mar 28, Mar 29, Mar 30, Mar 31, Apr 1, Apr 2, Apr 3, Apr 4, Apr 5, Apr 6, Apr 7, Apr 8, Apr 9, Apr 10, Apr 11, Apr 12, Apr 13, Apr 14, Apr 15, Apr 16, Apr 17, Apr 18, Apr 19, Apr 20, Apr 21, Apr 22, Apr 23, Apr 24, Apr 25\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=Legend\n|y1= 1, 5, 17, 24, 37, 39, 46, 82, 104, 106, 144, 155, 168, 181, 238, 295, 359, 430, 493, 539, 616, 808, 1071, 1139, 1544, 1704, 1941, 2226, 2278, 2391, 2698, 2757, 2830, 2987, 3058, 3222, 3370, 3561, 3780, 3955, 4068, 4212, 4352, 4479, 4580, 4588, 4591, 4673, 4877, 4916\n|y1Title=Confirmed \n|y2= 1, 5, 17, 24, 36, 37, 44, 78, 97, 99, 136, 144, 157, 169, 222, 270, 326, 395, 450, 492, 558, 732, 987, 1050, 1444, 1596, 1823, 2096, 2138, 2240, 2530, 2568, 2630, 2759, 2807, 2950, 3062, 3213, 3388, 3499, 3545, 3632, 3740, 3817, 3877, 3864, 3837, 3889, 4058, 4062\n|y2Title=Active \n|y3= , , , , , , , , , , , 2, 2, 2, 5, 9, 10, 11, 16, 18, 21, 25, 31, 31, 35, 36, 37, 38, 43, 50, 58, 67, 74, 97, 107, 119, 140, 167, 195, 247, 302, 338, 360, 399, 422, 434, 456, 474, 496, 516\n|y3Title=Recoveries\n|y4= , , , , 1, 2, 2, 4, 7, 7, 8, 9, 9, 10, 11, 16, 23, 24, 27, 29, 37, 51, 53, 58, 65, 72, 81, 92, 97, 101, 110, 122, 126, 131, 144, 153, 168, 181, 197, 209, 221, 242, 252, 263, 281, 290, 298, 310, 323, 338\n|y4Title=Deaths\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=900\n|colors=#FFC000\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|type=rect\n|x= Mar 6, Mar 8, Mar 9, Mar 10, Mar 11, Mar 12, Mar 13, Mar 14, Mar 